   New York's attorney general challenged an effort by the
federal thrift-bailout agency to evict eight renters from a
Manhattan condominium building seized by the government from
an insolvent savings and loan.
   In a strongly worded letter to Resolution Trust Corp.'s
executive director, David C. Cooke, state Attorney General
Robert Abrams said the tenants were entitled under the
state's rent control and stabilization laws to occupy the
apartments for as long as they wished.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The RTC said that the New York case is the first case in
which they have sought evictions, but that the agency was
prepared to do so whenever it was necessary to minimize
losses to U.S. taxpayers.
   The federal government is receiving roughly $9,000 per
month from the midtown apartments, while they are costing the
government about $27,000 per month, according to RTC
spokesman Stephen Katsanos.
   "Public protection shouldn't include throwing people out
of their homes," countered Richard Barr, a spokesman for the
attorney general.
   In August the RTC informed the eight tenants that the 1989
legislation creating the bailout agency gave the government
the right to repudiate their leases. The RTC then offered to
sell the apartments to the tenants.
   The apartments in question were foreclosed on by Nassau
Federal Savings &amp; Loan Association when the developer who
converted them into condominiums defaulted on his loan. The
RTC was appointed receiver of the thrift last March.
   In his letter, Mr. Abrams said that New York's Martin Act
bars owners from evicting renters when buildings are
converted to condominiums.
   "RTC should not reap windfall profits by transforming
occupied residential apartments into more valuable vacant
apartments by the draconian measure of evicting the
longstanding tenants of those apartments in violation of New
York law," Abrams wrote.
   Although the attorney general suggested that government
should sell the condominiums as occupied units, the market
for such units was nearly wiped out by the Tax Reform Act of
1986.
   John Jeffries Jr., a professor of constitutional law at
Virginia School of Law, said that although federal law
overrides state law, it is arguable whether Congress intended
to give the RTC the right to take such action.
   Mr. Abrams's office said that it hopes to persuade the RTC
to reverse its action, but that it was up to the tenants
involved to challenge the action in court.
   "No judge in New York is going to allow this," predicted
Errol Brett of New York's Schwartzseld, Ganfer &amp; Shore, which
represents hundreds of tenants associations. "The {federal}
statute doesn't apply to such situations at all."
