   INSURERS' TACTICS condemned by judge in toxic-waste
liability dispute.
   Investigators working on behalf of insurance companies
misled former employees of Monsanto Co. about the
investigators' identities and purposes, a state judge in
Delaware ruled.
   In the continuing litigation, the insurers argue that they
aren't liable for certain cleanup costs incurred by Monsanto,
a St. Louis chemicals company. The investigators were seeking
any information about Monsanto's operating practices that
might prove damaging to the company.
   Judge Vincent J. Poppiti ordered Travelers Corp., one of
Monsanto's primary insurers, based in Hartford, Conn., to
provide Monsanto with any former employees' statements
obtained by investigators. He said that evidence won't be
admissible at trial, scheduled to begin in September 1992.
Judge Poppiti didn't specifically blame Travelers for the
alleged misrepresentation.
   The judge also provided a script to be used by
investigators and lawyers when they initiate future
interviews of former Monsanto employees. Among other things,
the script requires the investigators to make clear that
Monsanto and the insurers are in litigation.
   Such high-stakes battles are increasingly common between
companies and their insurers over who should pay for the
burgeoning cost of cleaning up toxic waste allegedly released
by the companies. And insurers believe that interviews with
former employees can be effective in exposing wrongdoing by
the companies that might release the insurers from any
obligation to pay.
   In the Monsanto case, Judge Poppiti noted affidavits by
the former employees stating that, in some instances, the
investigators didn't disclose they represented the insurers.
For example, one former Monsanto employee was allegedly told
that an investigator "worked for a firm in New Orleans which
had been commissioned by the chemical industry to look into
which companies were polluting," according to the judge's
opinion. Two others were allegedly told that investigators
were "compiling a book" about a company plant, the judge
wrote.
   The judge acknowledged that some statements by the former
employees were contradicted by the affidavits of
investigators, but he still found evidence to conclude that
former employees were misled.
   The judge used strong language to condemn any dissembling.
"There is no vice that doth so cover a man with shame as to
be found false and perfidious," he wrote, quoting the
17th-century philosopher Francis Bacon.
   His order doesn't specify individual blame for
misrepresentation among the three dozen or so insurance
companies named by Monsanto as defendants, their outside
lawyers and independent investigators. It wasn't immediately
clear who, if anyone, coordinated the investigators' work.
   Travelers said in a statement that it didn't supervise the
investigators, nor did Travelers' outside lawyers supervise
them. Travelers also said it believes "parties to the case
will seek to clarify this point with the court."
   Judge Poppiti said the lawyers are accountable for the
investigators they retained, and he ordered the lawyers, not
their clients, to pay certain court costs of Monsanto.
